	abstract = {The number of people affected by diseases related to poor air quality has significantly increased over the years, totaling approximately 6.7 million deaths annually worldwide. However, a lack of specific applications to forecast air quality to warn the population about imminent risks remains. In this context, the literature presents various machine learning techniques that can be used for air quality forecast. However, for these techniques to be effective, datasets must be complete and free of missing values. This study employs the KNN Imputer algorithm to handle missing data. It compares different forecast algorithms, namely Prophet, Random Forest Regressor (RFR), and Long ShortTerm Memory (LSTM), with LSTM yielding the best results. The findings indicate that, although the data lack similarity, the forecast algorithms can closely follow actual values and provide daily air quality forecasts. This enhances the ability to efficiently warn the population about risks associated with exposure to atmospheric pollutants. © 2025 IEEE.},
